thread.title: WEEK 9: Region titles clinched, set-up in big night of prep football action

author: Morgan Lee
title: WEEK 9: Region titles clinched, set-up in big night of prep football action
text:
By Morgan Lee Sports Editor Gainesville's Messiah Dorsey, left, sizes up a Cedar Shoals defender in the Red Elephants' win on Friday in Gainesville. photo: David Weikel Related Articles 2015 High school football rankings 2015 High School Football region standings Red Elephants' whip Jaguars, set up showdown with Loganville Dawson blows past Banks to set up region championship shot 
A region title was sewn up, another region title shot was set up, and several over northeast Georgia-based programs saw their playoff pictures continue to clear on Friday in Week 9 of high school football action. 
Rabun County clinched its second straight Region 8-AA title courtesy a 43-10 defeat of Washington-Wilkes in Tiger. Meanwhile, Dawson County slammed Banks County 45-0 to help clear the way for a shot at the program's first-ever region title. 
As exciting as those results were, little could compare to the finishes at Fannin County and Winder-Barrow, however. West Hall traveled to Blue Ridge and pulled out a thrilling, 40-37 double overtime defeat of Fannin -- a result that also helped give the Tigers a title shot next week when they host Lumpkin County in Dawsonville. Also in 7-AAA play, East Hall knocked off Franklin County 34-27 in Carnesville to help keep the Vikings neck-and-neck with Dawson -- though the Tigers do have the edge due to their head-to-head win over East Hall earlier in the season. 
In Region 8- , Winder pulled off yet another thrilling win, knocking off Clarke Central 21-17. The win represented the Bulldoggs' fourth of the season decided by one possession and kept Winder in the thick of the playoff hunt. Also in 8- , Gainesville pulled away from Cedar Shoals 46-18 to right the ship after two straight defeats and set-up a big showdown at Loganville next week. Lanier kept a stranglehold on first in the region with a 31-10 defeat of Salem. 
Elsewhere, Habersham Central notched its first win of the campaign, 21-6 over Johns Creek in Region 6- . 
In Region 8-AAAA, North Hall maintained its push for the playoffs, blanking Monroe Area 25-0. Buford and Stephens County also maintained their undefeated marks in region play, the Wolves dominating North Oconee 56-7 and Stephens dumping Madison County 39-13. White County also kept its playoff hopes alive courtesy a 52-11 win at Chestatee. 
Mill Creek also kept its perfect record and drilled Collins Hill 42-17 to get off to a great start in its key three-game slate to end the 7- campaign. 
Be sure to check out our Friday Game Night page for game stories and video highlights from Week 9 action.
